        "text": "It was not the first time that the law enforcement officer had been accused of sexual abuse.\n\nBy the time of Christopher Michael Bauer’s 2021 arrest on charges of incest with a minor, sodomy in the first-degree and sexual abuse of a child under the age of 12, the Alabama state trooper had already allegedly skirted justice, according to the Montgomery County District Attorney’s Office.\n\nAs a special agent with the FBI, Bauer had previously been jettisoned from the New Orleans field office following several claims of sexual misconduct, according to Alabama prosecutors.\n\nBut he continued in his employment as an officer of the law, crossing state lines into Alabama with an allegedly forged letter — a copy of which PEOPLE obtained through the Associated Press – from an FBI official and gaining employment with the Alabama Law Enforcement Agency.\n\nIn the letter, dated Nov. 1, 2019, Bauer – purporting to be his acting unit chief – claimed to have been employed as a special agent for a ten-year span ending in September 2019.\n\nThe letter continued: “You are eligible for rehire without having to repeat New Agent Training for two years from the date you ceased employment.”\n\nIn reality, Bauer had been suspended without pay and lost his security clearance at the FBI’s New Orleans office in late 2018, a senior FBI official later confirmed to the AP.\n\nA co-worker had accused him of raping her at knife-point, the outlet reported. It is unknown if he has been charged in the alleged incident, which occurred in St. Tammany parish, according to the AP.\n\nBut the law enforcement officer’s alleged reign of terror was ultimately stopped by an unlikely source: an 11-year-old girl – who, now a young teen, recently testified that Bauer had been sexually abusing her since she was 5 years old – confided in a friend about the abuse, according to Alabama prosecutors.\n\nThe friend told her own mother, who reported it to girl’s school. School administrators called the Montgomery Police Department.\n\nThis time, law enforcement moved swiftly against one of their own, and, prosecutors say, police arrested and charged Bauer the same day. Bauer was held on a bond of $210,000, per his online booking record.\n\nWant to keep up with the latest crime coverage? Sign up for PEOPLE's free True Crime newsletter for breaking crime news, ongoing trial coverage, and details of intriguing unsolved cases.\n\nOn Friday, June 14, an Alabama jury convicted Bauer, now 44, of sodomy in the first degree and sexual abuse of a child under the age of 12.\n\n“Nobody is above the law, including our police officers,” District Attorney Daryl Bailey said in a statement. “If there’s a police officer who is committing a crime, in this case a crime against an innocent child, they are going to be prosecuted to the fullest extent of the law just like anybody else would.”\n\nCaptain Nick Manale of Louisiana State Police tells PEOPLE that their Special Victims Unit has active arrest warrants for Bauer in St. Tammany and Jefferson Parishes and that they plan to have him extradited to face unspecified charges “upon adjudication in Alabama.”\n\nIn Alabama, Bauer is slated for sentencing August 1, and faces up to 20 years to life in prison, per prosecutors, who plan to request the maximum sentence.\n\n“He needs to be removed from our streets forever,” Bailey said in the statement.\n\nPEOPLE could not reach Bauer's defense lawyer for comment.\n\nOf the child Bauer repeatedly abused, Bailey added: “She will always be haunted by what happened to her repeatedly over and over by this sexual predator,” but he said the conviction provided the family “a sense of justice.”\n\n“She knows this bad man will never be able to harm her ever again,” he said.\n\nIf you or someone you know has been a victim of sexual abuse, text \"STRENGTH\" to the Crisis Text Line at 741-741 to be connected to a certified crisis counselor."
